data.text:
**üñåÔ∏è API Artisan**

---

I‚Äôve been designing programming interfaces for over ten years, starting with a tiny string templating library called [FluTe](https://codeplexarchive.org/codeplex/project/flute "‚Äå").

I‚Äôve designed dozens of APIs since then, each one painstakingly crafted in a delicate compromise between legibility, power, intuitiveness and ‚Äì in commercial projects ‚Äì time.

- [parjs](https://github.com/GregRos/parjs "‚Äå") ‚Äì A parser-combinator library for TypeScript inspired by similar libraries for other languages.
- [zenesis](https://github.com/GregRos/zenesis "‚Äå") ‚Äì A ridiculously powerful library for generating TypeScript code.
- [Imms](https://github.com/GregRos/Imms "‚Äå") ‚Äì A data structure library with generic components.

**üåå Database Designer**

---

I‚Äôve designed database schemas from scratch, deciding on naming conventions, table structure, index placement, how the database is queried, and so forth.

I‚Äôve either ticked the ORM checkbox or avoided it due to different considerations each and every time. I firmly believe that question has no single answer.

**‚ôã Query Optimizer**

---

I‚Äôve optimized queries based on the query plan, ancient database lore, opposite day logic, astrology, and the promises of long-dead gods.

**üî≠ Exotic Query Proficiency**

---

Written all kinds of exotic queries for some reason or another. I‚Äôve done dynamic SQL, deeply recursive queries for processing tree data, and meta-queries about database structures.

**üóÇÔ∏è Database Generalist**

---

Worked with multiple database systems, thoroughly learning most of them:

- Microsoft SQL
- Postgres
- MySQL
- SQLite

I‚Äôve used several ORM frameworks, as well as query builders like Knex.

**üíé Beautifier of Logs**

---

Wrote a beautiful log formatter that used üåà **pretty colors** and üò∫_**emoji**,_ as well as making the logs more readable for the sake of other developers.

**üîî Definer of Alerts**

---

Defined lots of alerts for different metric states, such as job rates, low success rates, specific errors, critical events (crashes and so on), etc.

I made my own alerter daemon that interfaced with the slack API because I wanted the alerts to look just right.

**üìä Bringer of Metrics**

---

Designed and implemented system-wide metrics and alerts that could summarize the status and detect issues in a large scale production system.

These metrics involved histograms, different gauges, and statistical summaries. I set them using the badly documeted MQL metrics query language (GCP), and many of them involved quite tricky queries.

I‚Äôm always planning to move to Prometheus to avoid vendor lock-in, but it never seems worth it.

Made a pretty Grafana dashboard too!

**üîç Tracemaster**

---

Designed and implemented a distributed tracing system that could track any job as it passed through a different services, making it possible to quickly diagnose issues at every level of the system.

The system allowed lots of different log messages from different services and components to be associated with the same job.

Log message standardization allowed the system to be fully queryable.

**ü¶ë Web Protocol #@$%!!$**

---

I‚Äôve written software designed to extract as much information from an HTTP request as possible, running at massive scale, facing issues that could be blocks at different levels of the network stack.

I know my web protocols pretty well.

‚òÅÔ∏è Cloud Builder

---

I‚Äôve used observables on multiple different projects for processing different types of information on totally different platforms.

- RPC calls and messages

- Messages from a hardware device

üìù Open-Source Developer

---

Released many fully documented, comprehensively tested, and carefully designed open source libraries.

My work includes:

- [Preszr ](https://github.com/GregRos/preszr "‚Äå")‚Äì Efficient JS object graph serializer.
- [Wampus](https://github.com/GregRos/wampus "‚Äå") ‚Äì An RPC protocol client that heavily uses rxjs.
- [Zenesis ](https://github.com/GregRos/zenesis "‚Äå")‚Äì Schema-based code generation.

‚ö°Continuous Integrator

---

I‚Äôve set up CI/CD on multiple automation or deployment platforms:

- Bitbucket Pipelines
- GitHub Actions
- Google Cloudbuild

Deploying different codebases:

- Node.js
- Various client-sides
- C#

To different environments:

- Debian, Ubuntu, Alpine
- Windows Server
- Kubernetes, Docker

üìê Package Architect

---

Reorganized a codebase into a package architecture spanning a dozen or so interlinked packages, with carefully planned out dependency structures.

Published [22 public packages](https://www.npmjs.com/~gregros "‚Äå"), many of which are carefully designed, fully documented, and thoroughly tested libraries.

I‚Äôm really, really good at working with package-based codebases and I can make you one too.

üìöü¶ë Mastery of Specs

---

Worked closely to the ECMA-262 language specification for purposes like instrumenting and analyzing JavaScript source code.

Also worked with W3C specifications for various Web APIs, such as DOM, Geolocation, and so on.

üé≠ Anti-Purist

---

Paradigms are not answers, they are sets of abstractions that can be used to construct a system. These abstractions are basically separate tools sold as package deals, but you can rarely build anything with a single set of tools.

Instead, several sets of tools ‚Äì or abstractions ‚Äì should be used. This is the approach that most languages go with, combining OOP features with functional programming and other disciplines.

This is what engineering is ‚Äì taking abstract mathematical principles and turning them into tools for solving real world problems.

ü§î Skeptic (Object-Oriented Programming)

---

I‚Äôve been writing in object-oriented languages basically my whole life, which makes me sufficiently qualified to say that some aspects of this paradigm are overblown.

OOP patterns by themselves don‚Äôt lead to better code, and in fact some aspects (like methods) emphasize tight coupling that can be avoided using other approaches.

This is in contrast to functional programming principles, such as immutability, functional composition, and parametric polymorphism, which make code more predictable, powerful, and reusable.

üìö Yes, I Can Even Do Tech Support

---

I‚Äôve solved countless Windows issues in failed and working machines alike. I‚Äôve recovered data from failing hard drives, reconstructed drive metadata, fixed broken windows installations, and a whole lot more.

It comes with the territory of being a ü¶π‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Superpower User. If you install stuff that messes with internal components, you‚Äôre going to mess up eventually and then you‚Äôre going to need to fix your mess.

üìê GUI Craftsman

Spent most of my childhood building various kinds of desktop applications for Windows, using both Windows Forms and WPF.

ü¶π‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Superpower User

I work with a highly customized version of Windows, running beta and development builds as a matter of course to get the latest features.

I‚Äôve written a huge host of keyboard macros using AHK, many of which interface with internal Win32 systems like message queues, the Win32 API, COM, and the window system.

I‚Äôve used advanced Windows components, such as Group Policy, the registry, and so on to customize windows features when I feel like it. I‚Äôve also used undocumented COM interfaces I discovered using research.

I‚Äôve tried pretty much every type of WSL configuration you can think of.

I‚Äôve written Window Shell and VBS in the past, but I‚Äôm not keen to replicate the experience.

listing.name: Card Family
listing.description:
Every card deserves a family.  
Ever wanted a way to associate cards to each other in order to reflect sub-tasks, stories, etc?  
With **Card Family** you can do it easily. You only need this free Power-Up, with no 3rd parties involved.

It's an intuitive straight-forward solution. Just open a Trello card, and from a dedicated **Card Family** section - start associating other cards either as parents or children.

For a clearer view and progress indication you could also go to the Power-Up settings, and set different lists to different statuses - **Not Started**, **In Progress** and **Done**.


# Quick Overview

## Cards Creation

First step is to have a card
![Initial board](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/1.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Inside the card you'll see a new section - **Card Family**
!['Users' card](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/2.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Click on the *Children* button, and then click on the *Add Child...* link
![Selecting 'Children' and going to 'Add Child...'](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/3.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Choose *Create* if you want to create a new card, or *Search* if you want to associate an existing card
![Creating a child card for 'Users' - 'User Login' @ STORIES list](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/4.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

This is how it looks like when a card has a child
!['Users' card has a child - 'User Login'](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/5.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You could see if a card has children and/or parents by dedicated badges
![Badges representation](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/6.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

If you'll click on the newly created card you could see it already has the original card associated to it as parent
!['User Login' card](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/7.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

--------

Add a new child card, from the current child card
![Creating a child card for 'User Login' - 'Build a Login Form' @ SUB-TASKS list](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/8.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

![Badges representation](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/9.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You could see now the grandparent of the new card (the parent of the parent)
![Grandparent display](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/10.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

And the grandchild of the original card (the child of the child)
![Grandchildren display](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/11.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

--------

## Setting Lists as Status Indicators

If you have different lists for different statuses (e.g. a Kanban board) in which you have to-do/doing/done representations
![Kanban like board](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/12.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You can configure the **Card Family** Power Up to display the cards with a color indication of the status.  
Simply go to *Edit Power Up Settings*
![Edit settings](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/13.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Then select the relevant lists for each category
![Status categories empty](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/14.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)
![Status categories filled](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/15.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)

--------

You will see a badge indicating how many **done** children exists
!["Done" children badge](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/16.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

And you could see the different cards with the responsive color indicating their status
![Status colors](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/17.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)

listing.name: Card Size by Screenful
listing.description:
[Card Size by Screenful](https://screenful.com/card-size-for-trello/?utm_campaign=card_size_pul&utm_source=card_size_pu) is a **free Power-Up** that allows you to set weights (e.g. hours or story points) for your cards to estimate how much work each card requires. The estimate is shown in the card front. It‚Äôs a simple board utility that is free and runs entirely within the Trello UI. 

**Features**

- **Set weights** for your cards to estimate required work
- **See totals** by card assignee, label or list 
- Control information visibility on **card front and back**

**Card Size Power Up in action**

![Card Size Power Up animation](https://app.screenful.me/integrations/trello-card-size/cardsize_animation_small.gif)

---
   
**It's free so you can just add it to your board**. Learn more about [Card Size by Screenful](https://screenful.com/card-size-for-trello?utm_source=trello&utm_campaign=card_size_pu).
---

##More Power-Ups by Screenful

**[Analytics & Reports](https://trello.com/power-ups/5ee35178e3c7ec205df09613/analytics-reports-by-screenful)** allows you to share important insights with custom reports made from your Trello data. Save time with templates used by the industry‚Äôs best-performing teams!

**[Dashboards](https://trello.com/power-ups/570262ea1100fa611d7e200a/dashboards-by-screenful)** allow you to create sprints and releases, track your lead & cycle times, and see other key metrics on a single screen!

**[Scaled](https://screenful.com/scaled-for-trello)** is the all-in-one toolkit to your Trello boards to enable tracking work in scale. You can create epics, track dependencies between cards, and set estimates and priorities for cards. It gives you the power to manage and track work on a high level across multiple boards.

**[Epic Cards](https://screenful.com/epics-for-trello)** allows you to group cards into larger bodies of work, epics.

**[Card Dependencies](https://screenful.com/card-dependencies-for-trello)** allows you to link cards together by setting dependencies between them.

**[Card Priority](https://screenful.com/card-priority-for-trello)** allows you to set priorities and sort cards according to their importance.

listing.name: Card Family
listing.description:
Every card deserves a family.  
Ever wanted a way to associate cards to each other in order to reflect sub-tasks, stories, etc?  
With **Card Family** you can do it easily. You only need this free Power-Up, with no 3rd parties involved.

It's an intuitive straight-forward solution. Just open a Trello card, and from a dedicated **Card Family** section - start associating other cards either as parents or children.

For a clearer view and progress indication you could also go to the Power-Up settings, and set different lists to different statuses - **Not Started**, **In Progress** and **Done**.


# Quick Overview

## Cards Creation

First step is to have a card
![Initial board](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/1.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Inside the card you'll see a new section - **Card Family**
!['Users' card](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/2.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Click on the *Children* button, and then click on the *Add Child...* link
![Selecting 'Children' and going to 'Add Child...'](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/3.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Choose *Create* if you want to create a new card, or *Search* if you want to associate an existing card
![Creating a child card for 'Users' - 'User Login' @ STORIES list](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/4.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

This is how it looks like when a card has a child
!['Users' card has a child - 'User Login'](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/5.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You could see if a card has children and/or parents by dedicated badges
![Badges representation](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/6.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

If you'll click on the newly created card you could see it already has the original card associated to it as parent
!['User Login' card](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/7.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

--------

Add a new child card, from the current child card
![Creating a child card for 'User Login' - 'Build a Login Form' @ SUB-TASKS list](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/8.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

![Badges representation](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/9.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You could see now the grandparent of the new card (the parent of the parent)
![Grandparent display](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/10.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

And the grandchild of the original card (the child of the child)
![Grandchildren display](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/11.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

--------

## Setting Lists as Status Indicators

If you have different lists for different statuses (e.g. a Kanban board) in which you have to-do/doing/done representations
![Kanban like board](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/12.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

You can configure the **Card Family** Power Up to display the cards with a color indication of the status.  
Simply go to *Edit Power Up Settings*
![Edit settings](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/13.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

Then select the relevant lists for each category
![Status categories empty](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/14.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)
![Status categories filled](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/15.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)

--------

You will see a badge indicating how many **done** children exists
!["Done" children badge](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/16.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)  

And you could see the different cards with the responsive color indicating their status
![Status colors](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/trello-power-up-card-family.appspot.com/o/17.png?alt=media&token=4a3de166-a1d6-4d3b-8fe6-e865c1ec6a8a)
listing.overview: Associate cards with each other on a parents-to-children relationship

listing.name: Font Keren
listing.description:
The [Font Keren](https://www.fontkeren.info) Power-Up for Trello can help you give your board and card titles and descriptions a customized and attractive touch. You can edit the names of your boards and cards using cool and fancy fonts.
The Font Keren Power-Up generates multiple outputs at once and you can pick whichever one you like the best.
Here is how you can use the Power-Up to edit your board names and descriptions:
![Font Keren Screenshot 1](https://phpstack-666447-3200053.cloudwaysapps.com/publish_assets/font-keren-for-trello-3.gif)
-Click on the ‚ÄòFont Keren‚Äô Power-Up button
-Click on the ‚ÄòBoard Name Font‚Äô or ‚ÄòBoard Desc Font‚Äô
-Click on the ‚ÄòReset Font‚Äô for reset all cards and Board fonts.
-Select the font type from the drop-down menu
-Click on the ‚ÄòSave‚Äô button
The new font style will automatically be applied to the selected space.
And here is how you can use the Font Keren Power-Up on the individual cards:
-Open the card that you want to edit
-Click on the ‚ÄòFont Keren‚Äô button on the side bar
-Click on ‚ÄòCard Name Font‚Äô and ‚ÄòCard Desc Font‚Äô
-Select the font type from the drop-down menu
-Click on the ‚ÄòSave‚Äô button
listing.overview: Make your board and card fonts attractive with the Font Keren Power-Up.

listing.description:
The [Font Keren](https://www.fontkeren.info) Power-Up for Trello can help you give your board and card titles and descriptions a customized and attractive touch. You can edit the names of your boards and cards using cool and fancy fonts.
The Font Keren Power-Up generates multiple outputs at once and you can pick whichever one you like the best.
Here is how you can use the Power-Up to edit your board names and descriptions:
![Font Keren Screenshot 1](https://phpstack-666447-3200053.cloudwaysapps.com/publish_assets/font-keren-for-trello-3.gif)
-Click on the ‚ÄòFont Keren‚Äô Power-Up button
-Click on the ‚ÄòBoard Name Font‚Äô or ‚ÄòBoard Desc Font‚Äô
-Click on the ‚ÄòReset Font‚Äô for reset all cards and Board fonts.
-Select the font type from the drop-down menu
-Click on the ‚ÄòSave‚Äô button
The new font style will automatically be applied to the selected space.
And here is how you can use the Font Keren Power-Up on the individual cards:
-Open the card that you want to edit
-Click on the ‚ÄòFont Keren‚Äô button on the side bar
-Click on ‚ÄòCard Name Font‚Äô and ‚ÄòCard Desc Font‚Äô
-Select the font type from the drop-down menu
-Click on the ‚ÄòSave‚Äô button
